<section class="guidelines landing-guide" id="guidelines">
  <div class="help-header"><h2>Frequency Response Test Guide</h2><p>How to run a safe, honest hearing-range and speaker-response check in your browser.</p></div>
  <div class="help-grid">
    <div class="help-card"><h3>Step 1: quiet your room</h3><ol><li>Close windows, stop fans or AC if possible. Background noise masks the ends of the spectrum.</li><li>Mute notifications &mdash; a single ding during the sweep ruins the run.</li><li>Turn system volume to 20-30% before pressing Start. Sine tones sound louder than music at the same level.</li></ol></div>
    <div class="help-card"><h3>Step 2: run the sweep</h3><ol><li>Pick a duration: 25 s is a good balance (fast enough to stay focused, slow enough to catch roll-off).</li><li>Press "Start sweep". The readout ramps from 20 Hz upward on a log scale.</li><li>Press "I hear it now (low)" the moment you first hear sound &mdash; that is your low-end limit (or your speaker's low-end limit, whichever comes first).</li><li>Press "Stopped hearing (high)" when the tone fades into silence near the top. That is your high-end ceiling.</li></ol></div>
    <div class="help-card"><h3>Step 3: read your results</h3><ol><li>Healthy 20-year-olds: ~18-20 kHz ceiling. Ceiling drops roughly 2 kHz per decade of life (presbycusis).</li><li>A 1 kHz or 2 kHz ceiling almost certainly means your speaker or laptop is rolling off, not your ears. Try decent headphones.</li><li>Below 40-60 Hz most small drivers give up. Silence there is expected on phones, laptops, and earbuds.</li></ol></div>
    <div class="help-card"><h3>Manual mode</h3><ol><li>Drag the "Hold a specific frequency" slider to park on any Hz value.</li><li>Useful for checking a suspected buzz, rattle, or resonance (e.g. does 120 Hz rattle a desk panel?).</li><li>Also useful for A/B comparing two headphones on the same test tone.</li></ol></div>
